FBIS3-26437 "drchi026_k_94004" FBIS-CHI-94-026 Document Type:Daily Report 8 Feb 1994 NATIONAL AFFAIRS Political & Social Continued Reports on Li Peng's Visit to South China Accompanied by Officials HK0602040094 Hong Kong WEN WEI PO in Chinese 5 Feb 94 p A2 HK0602040094 Hong Kong WEN WEI PO Language: Chinese Article Type:BFN [Unattributed report: "Li Peng Arrives in Shenzhen After Visiting Zhuhai"] [Text] A report from Shenzhen has indicated that State Council Premier Li Peng and his suite arrived in Shenzhen this morning [date as published] to start an inspection tour there and attend the inaugural ceremony linking the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant with the power supply grid on 6 February. Li Peng and his suite arrived at the Shekou ocean terminal from Zhuhai by hovercraft at 1030 today. Emerging from the terminal, Li Peng headed for downtown Shenzhen by car under strict escort. Accompanying Li Peng on his inspection tour were Zou Jiahua, vice premier of the State Council; Lu Ping, director of the State Council Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office; Xie Fei, secretary of the Guangdong Provincial Party Committee; and Li Hao, vice chairman of the Financial and Economic Committee of the National People's Congress Standing Committee and senior adviser to Shenzhen City. Li Youwei, Shenzhen City Party Committee secretary and mayor, and other city leaders, including Wang Zhongfu, Lin Zuji, Zhu Yuening, He Jinghuan, and Huang Liman, greeted Li Peng at the Shekou terminal. Also present at the terminal to welcome the visitor were Wang Quanguo, president of the Guangdong Nuclear Power Joint-Venture Company, and Zan Yunlong, the company's general manager. Li Peng and his suite stayed in the guest house this afternoon and heard briefings by officials from the Shenzhen city party committee, the city government, and other departments concerned. It has been said that the briefings covered many areas and may need to be continued tomorrow. On Sunday [6 February], Li Peng and his suite will visit the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant to attend an inaugural ceremony linking the power plant with the power supply grid.
